's Special Forces Warrant Officer Institute</center>\nFile:US Army Special Warfare Education Group Flash.png|<center>SWCS's Special Warfare Education Group</center>\nFile:US Army Special Warfare Medical Group Flash.png|<center>SWCS's Special Warfare Medical Group</center>\nFile:US Army Special Warfare NCO Academy Flash.png|<center>SWCS's Special Warfare [[Non-Commissioned Officer]] Academy</center>\nFile:US Army Special Warfare Training Group Flash.png|<center>SWCS's 1st Special Warfare Training Group</center>\nFile:US Army 18th Airborne Corps NCO Academy Flash.png|<center>[[XVIII Airborne Corps]]'s [[Enlisted Professional Military Education|Non-Commissioned Officer Academy]]</center>\nFile:US Army Advanced Airborne School Flash.png|<center>[[82nd Airborne Division]]'s [[United States Army Jumpmaster School|Advanced Airborne School]]</center>\n</gallery>\n\n===US Air Force===\n<gallery>\nFile:USAF Combat Aviation Advisor flash.svg|<center>Combat Aviation Advisor ([[6th Special Operations Squadron]] (SOS) and [[711th Special Operations Squadron|711th SOS]])</center>\nFile:USAF Combat Controller Flash.jpg|<center>[[United States Air Force Combat Control Team|Combat Controller]]</center>\nFile:USAF Combat Rescue Officer Flash.png|<center>[[Combat rescue officer|Combat Rescue Officer]]</center>\nFile:USAF Pararescue Flash.jpg|<center>[[Pararescueman]]</center>\nFile:USAF Security Forces beret flash.jpg|<center>[[United States Air Force Security Forces|Security Forces]]</center>\nFile:USAF Security Forces flash-Officer.png|<center>Security Forces Officer</center>\nFile:USAF Special Reconnaissance Flash.png|<center>[[United States Air Force Special Reconnaissance|Special Reconnaissance]]</center>\nFile:USAF Special Tactics Officer Flash.png|<center>[[United States Air Force Special Tactics Officer|Special Tactics Officer]]</center>\nFile:USAF SERE Flash.jpg|<center>[[Survival, Evasion, Resistance and Escape]] Instructor</center>\nFile:USAF Tactical Air Control Party Beret Flash.svg|<center>[[United States Air Force Tactical Air Control Party|Tactical Air Control Party]]</center>\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Obsolete badges of the United States military]]\n* [[Badges of the United States Air Force]]\n* [[Uniforms of the United States Air Force]]\n* [[Uniforms of the United States Navy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{US Army uniforms}}\n{{US Army navbox}}\n{{US Air Force navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:United States Military Beret Flash}}\n[[Category:Heraldry of the United States Army]]\n", "name_user": "McChizzle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUS Army:Minor image formating and description edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_military_beret_flash"}
{"title_page": "Best Products", "text_new": "{{for2|the home electronics chain|[[Best Buy]]|the New York department store|[[Best & Company]]}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Best Products Co, Inc.\n| logo = Best Products logo.svg\n| type = [[Public company|Public]] ([[NASDAQ]]: BESTQ)\n| foundation = 1957\n| founder    = [[Sydney Lewis]]\n| defunct = February 1997 (liquidation completed in December 1998)\n| fate = [[Chapter 11 bankruptcy]] [[liquidation]]\n| location = [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n| industry = [[Retail]] ([[Catalog merchant]] showroom)\n| products = Home furnishings, consumer electronics, jewelry, housewares, toys\n| subsid = Ashby's, Basco, Dolgin's, Great Western, [[Jafco]], Labelle's, Miller Sales, Modern Merchandising, Rogers\n}}\n'''Best Products''' (also known simply as '''BEST''') was a chain of [[United States|American]] [[catalog showroom]] retail stores founded by Sydney and Frances Lewis, formerly headquartered in [[Richmond, Virginia]]. It was founded in 1957 and went out of business in 1997. At the time it filed the second time for bankruptcy, it had 169 Best stores and 11 Best Jewelry stores in 23 states, and a nationwide mail-order service. When in operation Best Products was traded on the [[NASDAQ]] exchange as \"BESTQ\".\n\n== History ==\nThe company was founded by [[Sydney Lewis]] and Frances Lewis. Sydney Lewis, a [[lawyer]] educated at [[Washington & Lee]] and [[Harvard Business School]], worked with his father managing an encyclopedia sales operation in Richmond. Lewis thought of selling additional merchandise along with the bills for encyclopedias. In 1957, the Lewises sent out their first catalog. The first showroom was at 4909 West Marshall Street in Richmond, just across the street from the new [[The Shops at Willow Lawn|Willow Lawn Shopping Center]].\n\nThe company had a strong sense of promotion and artistic sensibilities; it was legend in artistic circles that it would trade store merchandise for art. As a result, the company, as well as the Lewises, gathered a significant collection of 20th-century art. Much of the Lewis Collection can be seen at the [[Virginia Museum of Fine Arts]].\n\n=== Sculpture in the Environment ===\nIn the 1970s, Best Products contracted with [[James Wines]]' \"[[Sculpture in the Environment]]\" (SITE) architecture firm to design nine highly unorthodox retail facilities, notably a tongue-in-cheek structure called the \"Indeterminate Facade\" in [[Houston, Texas]] with a severely distressed facade. This building purportedly \"appeared in more books on 20th-century architecture than photographs of any other modern structure\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.texaschapbookpress.com/magellanslog54/indeterminatefacadeintro.htm |title=Bye-bye, Best Products: An Architecture Fairy Tale |accessdate=August 8, 2015 |website=Magellan's Log |publisher=Texas Chapbook Press |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060827012947/http://www.texaschapbookpress.com/magellanslog54/indeterminatefacadeintro.htm |archivedate=August 27, 2006 |url-status=dead |first=Diebold |last=Essen |date=August 2003}}</ref> In Richmond, the company built the Peeling Wall showroom that appeared to have a peeling facade (located on [[Midlothian Turnpike]]) as well as a Forest showroom that appeared to have trees growing out of it (located at 9008 [[Quioccasin Road]]). The store in Sacramento also had a unique design. In the morning, its corner entryway would slide open, and would slide back shut at night. The structure, with its breakaway entry removed, is now a Best Buy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mall-hall-of-fame.blogspot.com/2009/01/outparcel-best-products-store-at-arden.html |title=Best Products Arden Fair, Sacramento |date=January 12, 2009 |accessdate=August 8, 2015 |website=Mall Hall of Fame blog |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref> Photographs of these storefronts appeared in several Best catalogs. One anchored the [[Eudowood Plaza]] in [[Towson, Maryland]], featuring a tilted front. As of 2007, most of these distinctive buildings have been converted into conventional buildings by removing the architectural embellishments, or in a few cases, demolished. The only building to retain its distinctive features is the Forest building in Richmond, now home to the West End Presbyterian Church, which has stated that the forest in the entryway has been an asset to the church's environment.\n\nTheir Parham Road headquarters, built in 1981 and designed by [[Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer]], was notable for an American Institute of Architects award and the use of [[Art Deco]] eagles rescued from a New York building.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.henricomonthly.com/news/the-best-of-times |title=The Best of Times: Best Plaza awaits its next chapter |accessdate=August 8, 2015 |last=Griset |first=Rich |publisher=Henrico Monthly |date=<!--undated-->}}</ref> The giant BEST letters of the headquarters could be seen along Interstate 95 at Parham Road. Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer subsequently designed the West Wing of the Virginia Museum, which was funded by the Lewises<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://modentechgadgets.blogspot.com/2020/04/top-gadgets-in-kitchen.html|title=Top 7 gadgets in Kitchen|website=Top 7 gadgets in Kitchen|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>.\n\n=== Retail concept ===\n\nBest employed the \"catalog showroom\" concept for many of its product offerings. Although some product categories (such as sporting goods and toys) were stocked in traditional self-serve aisles, the majority of products (notably consumer electronics, housewares, and appliances) were featured as unboxed display models. Customers were permitted to examine and experiment with these models, and if found to be desirable, they could be purchased by submitting orders to store personnel. Saleable versions of the merchandise (usually boxed and/or in its original packaging) would then be retrieved from storage and delivered to a customer service area for subsequent purchase.\n\n=== Acquisitions ===\nAs a cost-saving measure, Best jointly published its catalog with [[Service Merchandise]] (founded by [[Harry Zimmerman]]) and [[Modern Merchandising]] (founded by [[Harold Roitenberg]]), and had regional non-compete agreements with those chains.\n\nIn 1982, Best acquired catalog competitors: [[Basco (department store)|Basco]], a chain with 19 catalog showrooms in the Northeast and Ohio; and Modern Merchandising, headquartered in Minnetonka, Minnesota with 76 showrooms under the names [[LaBelle's]], [[Dolgin's]], [[Jafco]], [[Miller Sales]], Rogers and Great Western. This was followed by the acquisition of Ashby's, a 9-store women's clothing chain, and the opening of four Best Jewelry stores in Maryland, Virginia and the District of Columbia.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Guide to the Records of Best Product Co., Inc. |publisher=Virginia Historical Society |year=2002 |isbn=0-945015-22-4 |editor-last=Gilmour |editor-first=Laura E. |oclc=248421247}}</ref>\n\n=== Bankruptcy ===\n[[File:BestStore.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Terrarium facade of [[Hialeah, Florida]] showroom]]\nBest filed twice for [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 11]] bankruptcy protection. The first bankruptcy period began in January 1991 and lasted through June 16, 1994. The second and final filing was made on September 24, 1996. At the time of the second filing, Best operated 169 Best stores and 11 Best Jewelry stores in 23 states, and a nationwide mail-order service.\n\nBest Products was traded on the [[NASDAQ]] exchange as \"BESTQ.\" It was de-listed on November 29, 1996, and Best did not appeal the NASDAQ decision. The last Best stores closed on February 9, 1997.<ref name=ap-1997feb10>{{cite news |url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1997/Catalog-showroom-chain-closes-last-stores/id-ded4e3f2ce502d0a638344a136bf50f4 |title=Catalog-showroom chain closes last stores |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 10, 1997 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref><ref name=pi-1996oct08>{{cite news |url=http://articles.philly.com/1996-10-08/business/25667322_1_ocean-reef-management-stores-part-time-employees |title=Best Products To Shut 81 Stores, Lay Off 4,500 The Outlets In Cherry Hill And Delco Will Be Closed. The Bankrupt Chain Will Keep 88 Stores Open. |newspaper=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=October 8, 1996 |first=Jane M. |last=Von Bergen}}</ref><ref name=os-1997feb11>{{cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1997-02-11/business/9702100388_1_david-geffen-regency-realty-hsn |title=On The Record: Bankrupt Best Products closes last of its stores |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=February 11, 1997 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref><ref name=bs-1997may04>{{cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1997-05-04/business/1997124194_1_lbo-funds-buyout-lbo-deals |title=LBO funds might be poised for a comeback Assets large again, with new players joining usual sources |newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]] |date=May 4, 1997 |first=Jay |last=Hancock}}</ref> By May 1997, Best had liquidated most of its assets and was declared [[insolvency|insolvent]]. Best vacated its corporate headquarters in Richmond in January 1998 and mailed out final checks to unsecured creditors the following December (paying 96 cents per dollar owed).\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.siteenvirodesign.com/proj.best.php Official project webpage on SITE's website]\n* [http://hecsan.home.travelin.com/articles/BestProducts/ Former Best Products store converted to KIII TV studios]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081202160659/http://www.jckonline.com/article/CA635288.html JCK: Houston Jewelry Breaks Catalog Showroom Shackles]\n\n[[Category:Defunct retail companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1957]]\n[[Category:Catalog showrooms]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1991]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1996]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Retail companies disestablished in 1998]]\n", "text_old": "{{for2|the home electronics chain|[[Best Buy]]|the New York department store|[[Best & Company]]}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Best Products Co, Inc.\n| logo = Best Products logo.svg\n| type = [[Public company|Public]] ([[NASDAQ]]: BESTQ)\n| foundation = 1957\n| founder    = [[Sydney Lewis]]\n| defunct = February 1997 (liquidation completed in December 1998)\n| fate = [[Chapter 11 bankruptcy]] [[liquidation]]\n| location = [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n| industry = [[Retail]] ([[Catalog merchant]] showroom)\n| products = Home furnishings, consumer electronics, jewelry, housewares, toys\n| subsid = Ashby's, Basco, Dolgin's, Great Western, [[Jafco]], Labelle's, Miller Sales, Modern Merchandising, Rogers\n}}\n'''Best Products''' (also known simply as '''BEST''') was a chain of [[United States|American]] [[catalog showroom]] retail stores founded by Sydney and Frances Lewis, formerly headquartered in [[Richmond, Virginia]]. It was founded in 1957 and went out of business in 1997. At the time it filed the second time for bankruptcy, it had 169 Best stores and 11 Best Jewelry stores in 23 states, and a nationwide mail-order service. When in operation Best Products was traded on the [[NASDAQ]] exchange as \"BESTQ\".\n\n== History ==\nThe company was founded by [[Sydney Lewis]] and Frances Lewis. Sydney Lewis, a [[lawyer]] educated at [[Washington & Lee]] and [[Harvard Business School]], worked with his father managing an encyclopedia sales operation in Richmond. Lewis thought of selling additional merchandise along with the bills for encyclopedias. In 1957, the Lewises sent out their first catalog. The first showroom was at 4909 West Marshall Street in Richmond, just across the street from the new [[The Shops at Willow Lawn|Willow Lawn Shopping Center]].\n\nThe company had a strong sense of promotion and artistic sensibilities; it was legend in artistic circles that it would trade store merchandise for art. As a result, the company, as well as the Lewises, gathered a significant collection of 20th-century art. Much of the Lewis Collection can be seen at the [[Virginia Museum of Fine Arts]].\n\n=== Sculpture in the Environment ===\nIn the 1970s, Best Products contracted with [[James Wines]]' \"[[Sculpture in the Environment]]\" (SITE) architecture firm to design nine highly unorthodox retail facilities, notably a tongue-in-cheek structure called the \"Indeterminate Facade\" in [[Houston, Texas]] with a severely distressed facade. This building purportedly \"appeared in more books on 20th-century architecture than photographs of any other modern structure\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.texaschapbookpress.com/magellanslog54/indeterminatefacadeintro.htm |title=Bye-bye, Best Products: An Architecture Fairy Tale |accessdate=August 8, 2015 |website=Magellan's Log |publisher=Texas Chapbook Press |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060827012947/http://www.texaschapbookpress.com/magellanslog54/indeterminatefacadeintro.htm |archivedate=August 27, 2006 |url-status=dead |first=Diebold |last=Essen |date=August 2003}}</ref> In Richmond, the company built the Peeling Wall showroom that appeared to have a peeling facade (located on [[Midlothian Turnpike]]) as well as a Forest showroom that appeared to have trees growing out of it (located at 9008 [[Quioccasin Road]]). The store in Sacramento also had a unique design. In the morning, its corner entryway would slide open, and would slide back shut at night. The structure, with its breakaway entry removed, is now a Best Buy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mall-hall-of-fame.blogspot.com/2009/01/outparcel-best-products-store-at-arden.html |title=Best Products Arden Fair, Sacramento |date=January 12, 2009 |accessdate=August 8, 2015 |website=Mall Hall of Fame blog |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref> Photographs of these storefronts appeared in several Best catalogs. One anchored the [[Eudowood Plaza]] in [[Towson, Maryland]], featuring a tilted front. As of 2007, most of these distinctive buildings have been converted into conventional buildings by removing the architectural embellishments, or in a few cases, demolished. The only building to retain its distinctive features is the Forest building in Richmond, now home to the West End Presbyterian Church, which has stated that the forest in the entryway has been an asset to the church's environment.\n\nTheir Parham Road headquarters, built in 1981 and designed by [[Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer]], was notable for an American Institute of Architects award and the use of [[Art Deco]] eagles rescued from a New York building.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.henricomonthly.com/news/the-best-of-times |title=The Best of Times: Best Plaza awaits its next chapter |accessdate=August 8, 2015 |last=Griset |first=Rich |publisher=Henrico Monthly |date=<!--undated-->}}</ref> The giant BEST letters of the headquarters could be seen along Interstate 95 at Parham Road. Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer subsequently designed the West Wing of the Virginia Museum, which was funded by the Lewises.\n\n=== Retail concept ===\n\nBest employed the \"catalog showroom\" concept for many of its product offerings. Although some product categories (such as sporting goods and toys) were stocked in traditional self-serve aisles, the majority of products (notably consumer electronics, housewares, and appliances) were featured as unboxed display models. Customers were permitted to examine and experiment with these models, and if found to be desirable, they could be purchased by submitting orders to store personnel. Saleable versions of the merchandise (usually boxed and/or in its original packaging) would then be retrieved from storage and delivered to a customer service area for subsequent purchase.\n\n=== Acquisitions ===\nAs a cost-saving measure, Best jointly published its catalog with [[Service Merchandise]] (founded by [[Harry Zimmerman]]) and [[Modern Merchandising]] (founded by [[Harold Roitenberg]]), and had regional non-compete agreements with those chains.\n\nIn 1982, Best acquired catalog competitors: [[Basco (department store)|Basco]], a chain with 19 catalog showrooms in the Northeast and Ohio; and Modern Merchandising, headquartered in Minnetonka, Minnesota with 76 showrooms under the names [[LaBelle's]], [[Dolgin's]], [[Jafco]], [[Miller Sales]], Rogers and Great Western. This was followed by the acquisition of Ashby's, a 9-store women's clothing chain, and the opening of four Best Jewelry stores in Maryland, Virginia and the District of Columbia.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Guide to the Records of Best Product Co., Inc. |publisher=Virginia Historical Society |year=2002 |isbn=0-945015-22-4 |editor-last=Gilmour |editor-first=Laura E. |oclc=248421247}}</ref>\n\n=== Bankruptcy ===\n[[File:BestStore.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Terrarium facade of [[Hialeah, Florida]] showroom]]\nBest filed twice for [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 11]] bankruptcy protection. The first bankruptcy period began in January 1991 and lasted through June 16, 1994. The second and final filing was made on September 24, 1996. At the time of the second filing, Best operated 169 Best stores and 11 Best Jewelry stores in 23 states, and a nationwide mail-order service.\n\nBest Products was traded on the [[NASDAQ]] exchange as \"BESTQ.\" It was de-listed on November 29, 1996, and Best did not appeal the NASDAQ decision. The last Best stores closed on February 9, 1997.<ref name=ap-1997feb10>{{cite news |url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1997/Catalog-showroom-chain-closes-last-stores/id-ded4e3f2ce502d0a638344a136bf50f4 |title=Catalog-showroom chain closes last stores |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 10, 1997 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref><ref name=pi-1996oct08>{{cite news |url=http://articles.philly.com/1996-10-08/business/25667322_1_ocean-reef-management-stores-part-time-employees |title=Best Products To Shut 81 Stores, Lay Off 4,500 The Outlets In Cherry Hill And Delco Will Be Closed. The Bankrupt Chain Will Keep 88 Stores Open. |newspaper=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=October 8, 1996 |first=Jane M. |last=Von Bergen}}</ref><ref name=os-1997feb11>{{cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1997-02-11/business/9702100388_1_david-geffen-regency-realty-hsn |title=On The Record: Bankrupt Best Products closes last of its stores |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=February 11, 1997 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref><ref name=bs-1997may04>{{cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1997-05-04/business/1997124194_1_lbo-funds-buyout-lbo-deals |title=LBO funds might be poised for a comeback Assets large again, with new players joining usual sources |newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]] |date=May 4, 1997 |first=Jay |last=Hancock}}</ref> By May 1997, Best had liquidated most of its assets and was declared [[insolvency|insolvent]]. Best vacated its corporate headquarters in Richmond in January 1998 and mailed out final checks to unsecured creditors the following December (paying 96 cents per dollar owed).\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.siteenvirodesign.com/proj.best.php Official project webpage on SITE's website]\n* [http://hecsan.home.travelin.com/articles/BestProducts/ Former Best Products store converted to KIII TV studios]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081202160659/http://www.jckonline.com/article/CA635288.html JCK: Houston Jewelry Breaks Catalog Showroom Shackles]\n\n[[Category:Defunct retail companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1957]]\n[[Category:Catalog showrooms]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1991]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1996]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Retail companies disestablished in 1998]]\n", "name_user": "DAY TO DAY NEWS", "label": "safe", "comment": "I have made some changes and provide some important details about gadgets.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Best_Products"}
{"title_page": "El amor las vuelve locas", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n | show_name          = El amor las vuelve locas\n | image              = Elamorlasvuelvelocas.jpg\n | num_episodes       = 151\n | genre              = [[Telenovela]]<br>[[Romance film|Romance]]\n | creator            = Leonardo Padr\u00f3n\n | writer             = Alberto G\u00f3mez<br>Silviano Su\u00e1rez<br>Haydee Ascanio\n | starring           = [[Lilibeth Morillo]]<br />[[Carlos Montilla]]<br />[[Jorge Aravena]]<br />Fabiola Colmenares<br />[[Juan Carlos Garc\u00eda (actor)|Juan Carlos Garc\u00eda]]<br>[[Marisa Rom\u00e1n]]\n | opentheme          =  \"El Amor Las Vuelve Locas\" by [[Alejandro Montaner]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cancionesdetelenovelas.com/cancion-de-la-telenovela-el-amor-las-vuelve-locas.html|title=Canci\u00f3n de la telenovela \u201cEl amor las vuelve locas\u201d|website=cancionesdetelenovelas.com|accessdate=21 July 2013|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914165758/http://www.cancionesdetelenovelas.com/cancion-de-la-telenovela-el-amor-las-vuelve-locas.html|archive-date=14 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n | endtheme           = \n | theme_music_composer = \t\n | language           = Spanish\n | country            = Venezuela\n | runtime            = 45 minutes\n | company            = [[Venevisi\u00f3n]]\n | distributor        = [[Cisneros Media Distribution|Venevisi\u00f3n International]]\n | location           = [[Caracas]]\n | channel            = [[Venevisi\u00f3n]]\n | audio_format       = \n | picture_format     = [[480i]] [[SDTV]]\n | first_aired        = February 16, 2005\n | last_aired         = July 19, 2005\n | executive_producer = Carolina de Jacobo\n | producer           = Manuel Federico Fra\u00edz-Grijalba\n | director           = Arqu\u00edmedes Rivero<br>C\u00e9sar Bolivar\n | cinematography     = \n | camera             = \n | editor             = \n | preceded_by        = ''[[Sabor a ti (telenovela)|Sabor a ti]]''\n | followed_by        = ''[[Se solicita pr\u00edncipe azul]]''\n | related            = ''[[Contra viento y marea (Venezuelan telenovela)|Contra viento y marea]] (1997)''\n | website_title      = \n | production_website =\n}}\n'''''El amor las vuelve locas''''' (English title: ''Love makes them crazy'') is a Venezuelan [[telenovela]] produced by [[Venevisi\u00f3n]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cisnerosmediadist.com/media/el-amor-las-vuelve-locas|title=El Amor las Vuelve Locas|website=cisnerosmediadist.com|accessdate=21 July 2013}}</ref> The series is a remake of the telenovela ''[[Contra viento y marea (Venezuelan telenovela)|Contra viento y marea]]'' written by Leonardo Padr\u00f3n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diariolavoz.net/2014/07/06/recordando-que-el-amor-las-vuelve-locas/|title=Recordando que\u2026 \u201cEl amor las vuelve locas\u201d|website=diariolavoz.net|accessdate=21 July 2013}}</ref>, and this new version was adapted by Alberto G\u00f3mez. The telenovela lasted for 151 episodes and was distributed internationally by [[Cisneros Media Distribution|Venevisi\u00f3n International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vencor.narod.ru/films/locas.htm|title=VENEVISION (2005), 151 capitulos El Amor Las Vuelve Locas|website=vencor.narod|accessdate=21 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Lilibeth Morillo]] and [[Carlos Montilla]] starred as the main protagonists with [[Jorge Aravena]], Fabiola Colmenares and Loly S\u00e1nchez as antagonists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.series-telenovelas.com/telenovelas-venezolanas/el-amor-las-vuelve-locas.htm|title=Protagonistas de telenovela \"El amor las vuelve locas\"|website=series-telenovelas.com|accessdate=21 July 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref> \n\n==Plot==\nFor 20 years, Fernanda has been unhappily married to Arnaldo, a wealthy and cruel man who is a womanizer and disregards Fernanda's feelings. While she was 18, Fernanda was in love with Pablo and they planned to marry. However, the brutal murder of her older brother changed Fernanda's life forever, as Pablo was accused of the crime. Through the evil schemes of her family, especially her overbearing mother, they convinced her that Pablo was dead and forced her into marrying Arnaldo.\n\nDestiny brings her face to face with her past lover Pablo who has been released from prison, determined to exact revenge on those who falsely accused him and clear his name of the crime he was accused of. On seeing Pablo, Fernanda finds herself at a crossroads where she has conflicting feelings- on one hand, she is stuck in a dead marriage to a man she doesn't love, while on the other, she can find true happiness again with her past lover. Furthermore, Fernanda has been hiding a terrible secret. Her daughter, Ana Maria, is not Arnaldo's as everyone thinks, but Pablo's.\n\nThese two will have to face the lies, conflicts and sources that prevent them from regaining true happiness and love.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telenovelasplus.com/argumento-de-el-amor-las-vuelve-locas.html|title=Argumento de \u201cEl amor las vuelve locas\u201d|website=telenovelasplus.com|accessdate=25 May 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n=== Main ===\n* [[Lilibeth Morillo]] as ''Fernanda Santana de Arismendi''\n* [[Carlos Montilla]] as ''Pablo Mart\u00ednez''\n* [[Jorge Aravena]] as ''Arnaldo Arismendi''\n* Fabiola Colmenares as ''Raquel Espina''\n* [[Marisa Rom\u00e1n]] as ''Vanessa Montilla''\n* [[Juan Carlos Garc\u00eda (actor)|Juan Carlos Garc\u00eda]] as ''Guillermo \"Memo\" Morales''\n* Ana Karina Casanova as ''Ana Mar\u00eda Arismendi Santana''\n\n=== Secondary ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Nohely Arteaga]] as ''Mara Montilla''\n* [[Beatriz Vald\u00e9s]] as ''Scarlett Conde''\n* Henry Soto as ''Eduardo C\u00f3rdova''\n* Yanis Chimaras as ''Luciano Santib\u00e1\u00f1ez''\n* [[Gledys Ibarra]] as ''Irene P\u00e9rez''\n* [[Roberto Lamarca]] as ''Tob\u00edas San Juan''\n* Tania Sarabia as ''Olvido''\n* Alberto Alifa as ''Ignacio Aguirre''\n* Milena Santander as ''Pastora Cabrera''\n* [[Carmen Julia \u00c1lvarez]] as ''Amparo''\n* Chony Fuentes as ''Yolanda''\n* Loly S\u00e1nchez as ''Maximiliana Santana''\n* [[Daniela Bascop\u00e9]] as ''Rosaura Escobar''\n* [[Luis Ger\u00f3nimo Abreu]] as ''Emilio Aldana''\n* [[Mar\u00eda Antonieta Duque]] as ''Amapola Castillo''\n* Carlos Augusto Maldonado as ''Carli\u00f1o Costera''\n* Fernando Villate as ''Goliath Gonz\u00e1lez''\n* [[Rhandy Pi\u00f1ango]] as ''Alex''\n* [[Claudia La Gatta]] as ''Cristina Caudal''\n* [[Beba Rojas]] as ''Lily Fajardo''\n* Erika Schwarzgruber as ''Abiga\u00edl''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0450896|El amor las vuelve locas}}\n\n{{Venevisi\u00f3n telenovelas in 2000-2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amor Las Vuelve Locas, El}}\n[[Category:2005 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:Venevisi\u00f3n telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2005 Venezuelan television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2005 Venezuelan television series endings]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language telenovelas]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Caracas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n | show_name          = El amor las vuelve locas\n | image              = Elamorlasvuelvelocas.jpg\n | num_episodes       = 151\n | genre              = [[Telenovela]]<br>[[Romance film|Romance]]\n | creator            = Leonardo Padr\u00f3n\n | writer             = Alberto G\u00f3mez<br>Silviano Su\u00e1rez<br>Haydee Ascanio\n | starring           = [[Lilibeth Morillo]]<br />[[Carlos Montilla]]<br />[[Jorge Aravena]]<br />Fabiola Colmenares<br />[[Juan Carlos Garc\u00eda (actor)|Juan Carlos Garc\u00eda]]<br>[[Marisa Rom\u00e1n]]\n | opentheme          =  \"El Amor Las Vuelve Locas\" by [[Alejandro Montaner]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cancionesdetelenovelas.com/cancion-de-la-telenovela-el-amor-las-vuelve-locas.html|title=Canci\u00f3n de la telenovela \u201cEl amor las vuelve locas\u201d|website=cancionesdetelenovelas.com|accessdate=21 July 2013|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914165758/http://www.cancionesdetelenovelas.com/cancion-de-la-telenovela-el-amor-las-vuelve-locas.html|archive-date=14 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n | endtheme           = \n | theme_music_composer = \t\n | language           = Spanish\n | country            = Venezuela\n | runtime            = 45 minutes\n | company            = [[Venevisi\u00f3n]]\n | distributor        = [[Cisneros Media Distribution|Venevisi\u00f3n International]]\n | location           = [[Caracas]]\n | channel            = [[Venevisi\u00f3n]]\n | audio_format       = \n | picture_format     = [[480i]] [[SDTV]]\n | first_aired        = February 16, 2005\n | last_aired         = July 19, 2005\n | executive_producer = Carolina de Jacobo\n | producer           = Manuel Federico Fra\u00edz-Grijalba\n | director           = Arqu\u00edmedes Rivero<br>C\u00e9sar Bolivar\n | cinematography     = \n | camera             = \n | editor             = \n | preceded_by        = ''[[Sabor a ti (telenovela)|Sabor a ti]]''\n | followed_by        = ''[[Se solicita pr\u00edncipe azul]]''\n | related            = ''[[Contra viento y marea (Venezuelan telenovela)|Contra viento y marea]] (1997)''\n | website_title      = \n | production_website =\n}}\n'''''El amor las vuelve locas''''' (English title: ''Love makes them crazy'') is a Venezuelan [[telenovela]] produced by [[Venevisi\u00f3n]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cisnerosmediadist.com/media/el-amor-las-vuelve-locas|title=El Amor las Vuelve Locas|website=cisnerosmediadist.com|accessdate=21 July 2013}}</ref> The series is a remake of the telenovela ''[[Contra viento y marea (Venezuelan telenovela)|Contra viento y marea]]'' written by Leonardo Padr\u00f3n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diariolavoz.net/2014/07/06/recordando-que-el-amor-las-vuelve-locas/|title=Recordando que\u2026 \u201cEl amor las vuelve locas\u201d|website=diariolavoz.net|accessdate=21 July 2013}}</ref>, and this new version was adapted by Alberto G\u00f3mez. The telenovela lasted for 151 episodes and was distributed internationally by [[Cisneros Media Distribution|Venevisi\u00f3n International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vencor.narod.ru/films/locas.htm|title=VENEVISION (2005), 151 capitulos El Amor Las Vuelve Locas|website=vencor.narod|accessdate=21 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Lilibeth Morillo]] and [[Carlos Montilla]] starred as the main protagonists with [[Jorge Aravena]], Fabiola Colmenares and Loly S\u00e1nchez as antagonists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.series-telenovelas.com/telenovelas-venezolanas/el-amor-las-vuelve-locas.htm|title=Protagonistas de telenovela \"El amor las vuelve locas\"|website=series-telenovelas.com|accessdate=21 July 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref> \n\n==Plot==\nFor 20 years, Fernanda has been unhappily married to Arnaldo, a wealthy and cruel man who is a womanizer and disregards Fernanda's feelings. While she was 18, Fernanda was in love with Pablo, a young man with whom she secretly planned to get married to. However, the brutal murder of her older brother changed Fernanda's life forever, as Pablo was accused of the crime. Through the evil schemes of her family, especially her overbearing mother, they convinced her that Pablo was dead and forced her into marrying Arnaldo.\n\nDestiny brings her face to face with her past lover Pablo who has been released from prison, determined to exact revenge on those who falsely accused him and clear his name of the crime he was accused of. On seeing Pablo, Fernanda finds herself at a crossroads where she has conflicting feelings- on one hand, she is stuck in a dead marriage to a man she doesn't love, while on the other, she can find true happiness again with her past lover. Furthermore, Fernanda has been hiding a terrible secret. Her daughter, Ana Maria, is not Arnaldo's as everyone thinks, but Pablo's.\n\nThese two will have to face the lies, conflicts and sources that prevent them from regaining true happiness and love.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telenovelasplus.com/argumento-de-el-amor-las-vuelve-locas.html|title=Argumento de \u201cEl amor las vuelve locas\u201d|website=telenovelasplus.com|accessdate=25 May 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n=== Main ===\n* [[Lilibeth Morillo]] as ''Fernanda Santana de Arismendi''\n* [[Carlos Montilla]] as ''Pablo Mart\u00ednez''\n* [[Jorge Aravena]] as ''Arnaldo Arismendi''\n* Fabiola Colmenares as ''Raquel Espina''\n* [[Marisa Rom\u00e1n]] as ''Vanessa Montilla''\n* [[Juan Carlos Garc\u00eda (actor)|Juan Carlos Garc\u00eda]] as ''Guillermo \"Memo\" Morales''\n* Ana Karina Casanova as ''Ana Mar\u00eda Arismendi Santana''\n\n=== Secondary ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Nohely Arteaga]] as ''Mara Montilla''\n* [[Beatriz Vald\u00e9s]] as ''Scarlett Conde''\n* Henry Soto as ''Eduardo C\u00f3rdova''\n* Yanis Chimaras as ''Luciano Santib\u00e1\u00f1ez''\n* [[Gledys Ibarra]] as ''Irene P\u00e9rez''\n* [[Roberto Lamarca]] as ''Tob\u00edas San Juan''\n* Tania Sarabia as ''Olvido''\n* Alberto Alifa as ''Ignacio Aguirre''\n* Milena Santander as ''Pastora Cabrera''\n* [[Carmen Julia \u00c1lvarez]] as ''Amparo''\n* Chony Fuentes as ''Yolanda''\n* Loly S\u00e1nchez as ''Maximiliana Santana''\n* [[Daniela Bascop\u00e9]] as ''Rosaura Escobar''\n* [[Luis Ger\u00f3nimo Abreu]] as ''Emilio Aldana''\n* [[Mar\u00eda Antonieta Duque]] as ''Amapola Castillo''\n* Carlos Augusto Maldonado as ''Carli\u00f1o Costera''\n* Fernando Villate as ''Goliath Gonz\u00e1lez''\n* [[Rhandy Pi\u00f1ango]] as ''Alex''\n* [[Claudia La Gatta]] as ''Cristina Caudal''\n* [[Beba Rojas]] as ''Lily Fajardo''\n* Erika Schwarzgruber as ''Abiga\u00edl''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0450896|El amor las vuelve locas}}\n\n{{Venevisi\u00f3n telenovelas in 2000-2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amor Las Vuelve Locas, El}}\n[[Category:2005 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:Venevisi\u00f3n telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2005 Venezuelan television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2005 Venezuelan television series endings]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language telenovelas]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Caracas]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_amor_las_vuelve_locas"}
{"title_page": "Arturo Castro (actor)", "text_new": "{{About|the Guatemalan actor|the Mexican actor|Arturo Castro}}\n{{short description|Guatemalan film and television actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{lead too short|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Arturo Castro\n| image         = Arturo Castro.jpg\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Castro in August 2016\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1985|11|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Guatemala]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = Guatemalan\n| other_names   =\n| occupation    = Actor\n| years_active  =\n| known_for     = Jaim\u00e9 Castro on ''[[Broad City]]''\n| notable_works =\n}}\n\n'''Arturo Castro''' (born November 26, 1985) is a Guatemalan actor best known for his portrayal of Jaim\u00e9 Castro on the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Broad City]],'' and David Rodriguez on the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Narcos]]''.\n\n==Career==\nCastro had hosted his own show on Guatemala's national network called Conexion a year before moving to New York City where he attended the [[American Academy of Dramatic Arts]], and where he met [[Abbi Jacobson]] and [[Ilana Glazer]] and got the role of Jaime in ''Broad City''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arturo-castro.com/about/|title=Who I Am - Arturo Castro|last=Castro|first=Arturo|date=|website=arturo-castro.com|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-28}}</ref> Castro had one of the leading roles in [[Ang Lee]]'s war drama ''[[Billy Lynn's Long Halftime Walk (film)|Billy Lynn's Long Halftime Walk]]'', playing Marcellino \u201cMango\u201d Montoya, a member of Billy Lynn's Bravo Squad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/Broad-City-Jaime-Arturo-Castro-Alternatino|title=Arturo Castro: 5 Things to Know About Broad City's Breakout Roommate|last=Lane|first=Laura|date=|website=people.com|publisher=Time Inc.|access-date=2016-08-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Arturo landed a role as David Rodriguez, son of a [[Cali Cartel]] kingpin, in season 3 of the Netflix Series [[Narcos]]. He also played Jose in ''[[Bushwick (film)|Bushwick]]'', a film about 20-year-old Lucy and war veteran Stupe depending on each other for survival when a Texas military force invades their Brooklyn neighborhood. He currently stars in [[Comedy Central]]'s ''[[Alternatino with Arturo Castro]]'', a sketch comedy show centering on life as a modern Latino man.<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/alternatino-arturo-castro-review-1219092</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Films===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Looking for Palladin''\n| Nestor\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"| 2009\n| ''Taught to Hate''\n| Antonio\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''The Likes of Us''\n| Mr. Franklin\n| \n|-\n| ''Lovebug''\n| Dennis 492\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''How to Come Home''\n| Billy\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''Cuando ya no me quieras''\n| Felipe\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''Behind Closed Doors''\n| Boyfriend\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''Adan''\n| Miguel Correo \n| Short film\n|-\n| ''Taught to Hate''\n| Antonio\n| Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 2010\n| ''Heaven Is Waiting''\n| Driver\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''Tiempo al tiempo''\n| Cisco\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''Fair Lawn''\n| Jose Aviles\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''The Troy Shawn Welcome Story''\n| Raymond\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''Apparition''\n| Omar\n| Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2011\n| ''Tobi''\n| \n| \n|-\n| ''Yi's Story''\n| Caesar\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''Come Home Raquel''\n| Luis\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2012\n| ''[[Indigo Children (film)|Indigo Children]]''\n| Armand\n| \n|-\n| ''Vivir Asi''\n| Tito\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''Caregiver''\n| Ricky\n| Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2014\n| ''[[Sun Belt Express]]''\n| Miguel\n| \n|-\n| ''Text Amy''\n| Luis Eduardo\n| Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\